<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="416" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[674,1211,913,1225]" box="[677,821,913,940]" pageId="7" pageNumber="416">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[674,1211,913,1225]" pageId="7" pageNumber="416">
Shell 
<quantity box="[734,817,944,971]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.9" pageId="7" pageNumber="416" unit="mm" value="7.9">7.9 mm</quantity>
long, well curved with the arc located at posterior ⅓ of shell, slowly tapering, opaque cream. Longitudinally sculptured with 48 fine striae and secondary ones that appear at the posterior ¼ of the shell. Apex simple circular, callus thin, lumen central, circular, large. Anterior aperture straight, circular.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[674,1211,913,1225]" pageId="7" pageNumber="416">
Measurements of 
<typeStatus box="[879,973,1166,1193]" pageId="7" pageNumber="416">holotype</typeStatus>
:L 7.9, W 0.63, w 0.32, arc 0.72 at 3.6 from apex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="416" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[674,1212,1261,1700]" box="[677,777,1261,1288]" pageId="7" pageNumber="416">REMARKS</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[674,1212,1261,1700]" pageId="7" pageNumber="416">
Breakages and repairs of unknown origin are present in all specimens studied. Compared to 
<taxonomicName authority="Scarabino &amp; Scarabino, 2010" authorityName="Scarabino &amp; Scarabino" authorityYear="2010" box="[1110,1209,1325,1350]" class="Scaphopoda" family="Gadilinidae" genus="Episiphon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dentaliida" pageId="7" pageNumber="416" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="joanae" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[1110,1209,1325,1350]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="416">E. joanae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[677,735,1356,1383]" pageId="7" pageNumber="416" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Scarabino &amp; Scarabino, 2010" authorityName="Scarabino &amp; Scarabino" authorityYear="2010" box="[788,884,1356,1382]" class="Scaphopoda" family="Gadilinidae" genus="Episiphon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dentaliida" pageId="7" pageNumber="416" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="wallisi" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[788,884,1356,1382]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="416">E. wallisi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[891,951,1356,1383]" pageId="7" pageNumber="416" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, the present new species has an intermediate number of striae, its arc is located posterior, the lumen is much larger due to its thin apical callus. 
<taxonomicName authority="(Boissevain, 1906)" baseAuthorityName="Boissevain" baseAuthorityYear="1906" box="[808,1210,1451,1478]" class="Scaphopoda" family="Gadilinidae" genus="Episiphon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dentaliida" pageId="7" pageNumber="416" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="truncatum">
<emphasis box="[808,1015,1451,1477]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="416">Episiphon truncatum</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="BOISSEVAIN M." box="[1027,1202,1451,1478]" pageId="7" pageNumber="416" pagination="1 - 76" refId="ref9529" refString="BOISSEVAIN M. 1906. - The Scaphopoda of the Siboga Expedition, treated together with the known Indo-Pacific Scaphopoda, in WEBER M. (ed.), Siboga Expeditie 54 (livraison 32): 1 - 76, pls 1 - 6. Brill, Leiden." type="journal article" year="1906">Boissevain, 1906</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
(
<typeStatus box="[682,778,1483,1510]" pageId="7" pageNumber="416">syntypes</typeStatus>
ZMA 3.06.065-067, examined) from 
<collectingCountry box="[678,784,1515,1542]" name="Indonesia" pageId="7" pageNumber="416">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
(
<quantity box="[801,878,1515,1542]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.81" pageId="7" pageNumber="416" unit="m" value="281.0">281 m</quantity>
), has almost similar breakages as 
<taxonomicName authority="Scarabino &amp; Scarabino, 2010" authorityName="Scarabino &amp; Scarabino" authorityYear="2010" box="[705,854,1546,1572]" class="Scaphopoda" family="Gadilinidae" genus="Episiphon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dentaliida" pageId="7" pageNumber="416" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="indefensum" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[705,854,1546,1572]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="416">E. indefensum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[862,922,1546,1573]" pageId="7" pageNumber="416" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
in adult specimens, but is much larger, solid, brilliant, the sculpture consists of encircling wrinkles in the apical sector and the apical section is roughly subtriangular. The apical callus of 
<taxonomicName authority="Scarabino &amp; Scarabino, 2010" authorityName="Scarabino &amp; Scarabino" authorityYear="2010" box="[675,820,1673,1699]" class="Scaphopoda" family="Gadilinidae" genus="Episiphon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dentaliida" pageId="7" pageNumber="416" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="indefensum" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[675,820,1673,1699]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="416">E. indefensum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[828,886,1673,1700]" pageId="7" pageNumber="416" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is clearly thin for the genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
